<p><strong>California Slender Salamander (<em>Batrachoseps attenuatus</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Plethodontidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Batrachoseps attenuatus</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>California Slender Salamander<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p> The California Slender Salamander has a body length of 1¼-1⅞ inches and a total length of 3-5½ inches. It has a narrow head, long body and tail, and very short limbs. It has a black or dusky belly; its tail underside is often lighter than the belly with a tinge of yellow. Its ventral surfaces are finely specked with white. There is often a dorsal stripe present ranging in color depending on location. Males have a more pointed lower jaw and broader snout. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.californiaherps.com/salamanders/pages/b.attenuatus.html">California Herps</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This salamander lives in grasslands, chaparral, woodlands, forests, yards, and vacant lots in some suburban areas. They can be found under logs, boards, bark, in damp leaf litter, and in rotting logs. Diet consists of a variety of invertebrates such as springtails, spiders, small beetles, snails, mites, and isopods. Eggs are laid in late fall and winter in communal nests and hatch within 72-86 days.</p>
